Here's a bullet point biography of Lawrence J. Fogel:

* Lawrence Joel Fogel was an American computer scientist and engineer, born in 1929 in New York City, USA.

* He earned his Bachelor's degree in Electrical Engineering from the City College of New York in 1950 and his Master's degree in Electrical Engineering from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) in 1951.

* Fogel made significant contributions to the field of evolutionary computation, particularly in the development of evolutionary programming (EP), which is a type of artificial intelligence that uses evolutionary principles to search for optimal solutions.

* He is also known for his work on simulated evolution and the use of evolutionary algorithms for solving complex optimization problems.

* In addition to his work on evolutionary computation, Fogel made significant contributions to the field of adaptive control systems, which are systems that can adapt to changing conditions.

* The Alto was also the first computer to use a bitmapped display, which allowed for high-resolution graphics and text.

* Thacker's work on the Alto was a significant influence on the development of the Apple Macintosh computer, which was released in 1984.

* In 1983, Thacker and his team at Xerox PARC developed the Ethernet network, which was the first local area network (LAN) to use a bus topology and a packet-switching protocol.

* Thacker was awarded the National Medal of Technology in 1999 for his contributions to the development of the Alto and Ethernet.

* He was also awarded the Marconi Award in 2001 for his contributions to the development of the Ethernet.

* In 2009, Thacker was inducted into the National Inventors Hall of Fame for his work on the Alto and Ethernet.

* Thacker is a fellow of the Association for Computing Machinery (ACM) and a member of the National Academy of Engineering.

* He has received numerous other awards and honors for his contributions to computer science and engineering, including the ACM A.M. Turing Award, which he received in 2009 for his contributions to the development of the Alto and Ethernet.

• In 1941, his family moved to the United States, and he settled in Ohio.

• Kemeny received his Bachelor's degree in mathematics from Princeton University in 1947.

• He then pursued his graduate studies at Princeton University and received his Ph.D. in mathematics in 1953.

• John Kemeny worked as a professor at Dartmouth College from 1953 to 1971, where he developed a strong interest in computer science.

• In 1964, he co-authored the book "Man-Computer Symbiosis" with Thomas E. Kurtz, which is considered a foundational work in human-computer interaction.

• Kemeny and Kurtz developed the BASIC programming language in 1964, which became widely used in the 1970s and 1980s.

• In 1965, Kemeny was appointed as the President of Dartmouth College, a position he held until 1981.

• During his tenure as President, Kemeny focused on developing Dartmouth into a more diverse and technologically advanced institution.

• He also established the Artificial Intelligence Laboratory at Dartmouth College in 1972, which was one of the first AI research centers in the world.

• John Kemeny received numerous awards for his contributions to computer science and education, including the ACM A.M. Turing Award in 1973.

• He passed away on December 26, 1992, leaving behind a legacy as a pioneering computer scientist and educator.

• Jurafsky has been recognized for his commitment to diversity and inclusion in the field of computer science, including being a founding member of the Association for the Advancement of Artificial Intelligence (AAAI) Diversity Committee.

 
• He has also been recognized for his commitment to public service, including being a member of the National Science Foundation's (NSF) Advisory Committee on Cyberinfrastructure.

 
• Jurafsky has also served as a member of the Stanford University Board of Trustees and has been a fellow of the American Association for the Advancement of Science (AAAS) since 2010.

 
• Throughout his career, Jurafsky has received numerous awards and honors for his contributions to computer science and linguistics, including being elected as a fellow of the Association for the Advancement of Artificial Intelligence (AAAI) in 2018.
